<h1>Japanese Phrases</h1>
<section>
<h2>しちてんはっき【七転八起】</h2>
<img class="item-detail_originImg_1eebd975" src="https://baseec-img-mng.akamaized.net/images/item/origin/97d7a2a8a082840a17e3639e9faf3fa6.jpg?imformat=generic&amp;q=90&amp;im=Resize,width=640,type=normal" width="480" height="480" loading="lazy">
<ul>
<li>七 is number 7. In this phrase, it must be read as しち "shichi".
<li>転 has a lot of uses, but for this phrase it will represent falling or downs and is read as てん "ten".
<li>八起 is a combo of number 8 はち "hachi" and get up き "ki". So, together, it must be read as "hakki". Why is kanji so hard?!
</ul>
<h3>How to Read this phrase: <em>shichi ten hakki</em></h3>
Transaltion: No matter how many times you fail, keep trying and never give up.
<section>
Please <strong>do not</strong> get a tattoo of this! <strong>It's permanent!</strong>
</section>
